Better handling of leading infix operators in indented code ```code @main def Test =   val x = false   val y = 1   val result =     x     || y.match         case 1 => false         case 3 => false         case _ => true     || !x   assert(result) ``` In this code
column8: the last `|| !x` was seen as a part of the previous case
column9: so the code was parsed as ```scala @main def Test =   val x = false   val y = 1   val result =     x     || y.match         case 1 => false         case 3 => false         case _ => true || !x   assert(result) ``` This is highly surprising and unintuitive. The fix will insert an <outdent> token instead if the leading infix operator is too far to the left. Too far means: (1) left of the current indentation region
column10: (2) and not to the right of any outer indentation widths.
